<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-057-131 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 316 955</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 19 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>1st printer with internal hard disk for que, fonts. (GeneralParametrics introduces Spectra Star Model 440 color thermalprinter) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rohrbough, Linda.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Parametrics Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    GPAR.andO;Product:   General Parametrics Spectra Star 440 (Computer printer) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Thermal printersColorProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****1ST PRINTER WITH INTERNAL HARD DISK FOR QUE, FONTS 09/19/91 BERKELEY,CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1991 SEP 19 (NB) -- General Parametrics says it hasintroduced the Spectra Star Model 440, a color thermal printer with thedistinction of being the first printer with its own internal 32-megabyte (MB)hard disk for print spooling and font storage.andM;General Parametrics says the printer completely frees the computer for othertasks by doing its own storage and spooling of a series of images, and byproviding permanent storage capacity for PostScript fonts.andP;  The storagecapacity for fonts allows the processing of files to increase and improvesoverall printer performance, the company said.andM;Herb Baskin, president and chief executive officer of General Parametricssaid, &quot;The spooling and font storage capabilities of the Spectra Star Model440 enable users to spend their time more productively by reducing the amountof time they spend waiting for their computers to send information to theprinter.&quot;andM;The printer prints at 300 dots-per-inch (dpi) and supports PostScriptinterpreters on both the IBM personal computer (PC) and Macintosh platforms,the company said.andP;  Hard disks of more than 32 MB are available, but must bespecial ordered, General Parametrics said.andM;The company said the Spectra Star Model 400 family includes thermal colorprinters that can be upgraded.andP;  The Model 430 retails for $6,995, includes areduced instruction set chip (RISC) processor, hardware PostScript capabilityand 6 MB of random access memory, and can be upgraded to the hard disk Model440 for $1,050.andP;  The Model 440 retails for $7,995, but can be upgraded for$6,995 to a Model 450 which includes a film recorder for producing 35mmPostScript slides, General Parametrics said.andM;The Model 450's retail price is $14,990.andP;  Both the film recorder upgrade andthe Model 450 are expected to be available in 1992, the company said.andM;(Linda Rohrbough/19910919/Press Contact: Harry Miller, General Parametrics,Tel: 415/938-5663, Fax: 415/510-524-9954)</TEXT></DOC>